Consider this snippet:

```
public class CCC
{
    void Foo()
    {
        string[] arr = null;
        string s = arr[0];
    }
}
```

If I invoke `GetIndexerGroup(node)` where node is `arr[0]` (an `ElementAccessExpressionSyntax`), I get, as the single result in the collection, the indexer property `string.this[int]`.

This seems wrong to me...

I could expect `null` or an “array indexer” (which returns an `string`); but not an string indexer (which returns an `char`). For instance, if I invoke `GetOperation(node)` on that same node, I correctly get a `IArrayElementReferenceOperation`.

```
    public static void Main() {
        A a = null;
        a.x = 1; 
    }
    
    class A
    {
        internal int x;
    
        internal void Store(int i)
        {
            this.x = i;
        }
    }
```
In `Main` attempting to `stfld` will throw a NRE.  In the instance method `Store` it's impossible isn't it to get in there without an object, so would the compiler be expected to optimise and not put the null check for the `stfld` here:

```
        .method assembly hidebysig 
            instance void Store (
                int32 i
            ) cil managed 
        {
            // Method begins at RVA 0x2061
            // Code size 8 (0x8)
            .maxstack 8

            IL_0000: ldarg.0
            IL_0001: ldarg.1
            IL_0002: stfld int32 C/A::x
            IL_0007: ret
        } // end of method A::Store
```

I suppose its not trivial as it would have to know that the first arg is `this`, but not that hard either to spot at least simple cases like this.
